      <group id="content" extype="content">
        <trans-unit id="101" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" extradata="MT" restype="x-metadata">
          <source>Add a new data source to a form</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" extradata="MT" restype="x-metadata">
          <source>This topic explains how you can add new data sources to existing forms by using extensions.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Add a new data source to a form</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Often, the information that is stored in existing tables doesn't satisfy customer requirements.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Therefore, additional tables must be created, and data from those tables must be shown on pages.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can add new data sources to existing forms through extension.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Follow these steps.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In the extension model, create a form extension for the selected form.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Right-click the form extension, and then select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>New Data Source<ept id="p1">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Add a form data source</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Specify the <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Table<ept id="p1">**</ept> property and other required properties on the data source.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For example, define how the data source should be linked with the other data sources for the form.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Drag fields from the new data source into the form design, as shown in the following illustration.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="114" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Add fields from the data source to the form design</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="115" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In a similar manner, you can add fields from existing data sources.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="116" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For example, the table behind the form might have been extended with additional fields, as shown in the following illustration.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="117" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Data source that has additional fields</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="118" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You might have to right-click the form extension data source and then select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Restore<ept id="p1">**</ept> to make the new fields appear in the list.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="119" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can now view and edit the data in these new fields and tables, as shown in the following illustration.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="120" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>New fields</source>
        </trans-unit>
